  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">CMDRR training and pilot project in Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1000 direct beneficiaries and 6000 indirect beneficiaries</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Cordaid and local organisation RRAA are present in Balkh province (the target area for this pilot project) for more than a decade through implementation of emergency and development projects in 5 districts (Dawlatabad, Khulm, Dehdadi, Balkh and Chimtal). Since mid-2007 RRAA is implementing more structural development programs with the aim of institutional capacity building of agriculture and livestock cooperatives and access to micro credit (15,000 USD/Cooperatives) and other interventions in supporting agriculture and livestock. The current program can build on this presence and good relationships within the communities.

Recently, Cordaid Afghanistan gained experience in a program with resilience aspects. In 2015, Cordaid together with other international organizations (Caritas Germany and Catholic Relief and Service) developed a joint program funded by the Ministry Foreign Affairs of Germany. The program is implemented in 5 provinces, including Balkh and is called &#x2018;Mitigating Migration Causes by Strengthening Local Coping Strategies in 2 districts of Balkh province&#x2019; with an implementation period of August 2016 &#x2013; December 2018. Cordaid and RRAA have gained good experiences and lessons learnt during the past two years of this German AA (Auswartiges Amt- Federal Foreign Office of German) project. Some of the results of this project are:

-	Establishment of 55 loan groups. They received 10,000 Euro per group as revolving fund, by which they have generated net profit of about 67,368 EUR (5,658,947 AFN). 
-	Job creation for about 1650 individuals through access to loan (zero interest)
-	Prevention of 200 migration cases outside country through loan provision
-	Avoided destruction of agricultural land and houses through construction of protection- and retaining walls
-	Improved water-management through construction of aqueducts and canals, access to drinking water through digging of wells and installation of solar pumps. 
-	Enhanced knowledge and skills of targeted community on WASH practices
-	Increased agriculture and livestock productivity (information from-project progress report and midline reflection report Dec 2017).</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Vulnerable social groups secure and resilient with livelihoods and have increased disaster risk reduction capacity, in 8 communities in Balkh province.</narrative>
  </description>
